Each of them was breathing soundly and comfortably in their sleep.

Judging from the way they were huddled together, it might have been a little cold.

"Well, it can't be helped..."

I covered the four of them, who were sleeping comfortably, with blankets, but there was no sign of them waking up.

Seriously, he's so cute when he's sleeping.

Well, he's cute normally, but it's a peaceful moment that makes it seem like his usual loudness was a lie.

Looking at Hinata and the others' sleeping faces, I couldn't help but be overcome with emotion.

This unexpected, noisy life wasn't so bad. In fact, it was fun.

I had no choice but to accept these kids and think that I would just have to be patient for a while, but now that I think that this time is only until the next full moon, it seems a shame.

Today is a new moon, which means I've already reached the halfway point of my life with these kids.

Even if there is no such separation, nothing lasts forever.

But the days, counting the days until the next full moon, seem too short.

If elves and humans have different life spans, then once they are separated, they will probably never see each other again.

I found myself praying to no one in particular that if only they could stay like this a little longer.

